<section id="anne_gentle">
  <title>Sprints and Stacks: Lessons in Documentation Community Building</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#anne_gentle"/></p>

  <p>You can build a documentation strategy within your community that
  harnesses collaborative energy, but it’s not easy. The payoffs are real
  in terms of increased adoption, download conversions, and connecting one
  community member to another, but there are pitfalls to avoid. OpenStack
  offers open source cloud computing software and we are a young project,
  less than a year old. Let’s discuss our approach to community documentation,
  doc sprints, licensing, translation, and volunteer writer management as
  a case study. I’ll talk about the expectations I had coming in to the
  project and the realities I’ve learned while implementing my vision.
  I know I have barely begun to tap the potential of this new
  community-oriented documentation skill set.</p>

  <list>
    <item><p><link href="http://www.slideshare.net/annegentle/sprints-and-stacks">Slides</link></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="janet_swisher">
  <title>Engaging developers in Mozilla’s documentation</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#janet_swisher"/></p>

  <p>The Mozilla Developer Network site provides documentation not
  for only developers working on or with Mozilla code, but also for
  web developers working with open web technologies. I’ll discuss
  various efforts for encouraging this diverse audience to participate
  in maintaining the documentation. Some of these are led by Mozilla,
  such as documentation sprints (both face-to-face and virtual) and
  “Wiki Wednesdays”. Others are from external sources, such as other
  browser vendors, and the grassroots “Promote JS” campaign. I’ll
  talk about how these strategies can be applied to other open source
  projects.</p>

  <list>
    <item><p><link href="http://www.slideshare.net/janetswisher/engaging-developers-in-mozilla-docs">Slides</link></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="dru_lavigne">
  <title>Starting an Open Source Certification Program</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#dru_lavigne"/></p>

  <p>A certification program adds another level of complexity to a
  project’s documentation efforts. It also provides opportunity for
  increased project exposure and product adoption. Furthermore, members
  of the project’s documentation team often have the knowledge and
  writing skills required by a certification program’s SMEs (subject
  matter experts) and authors of training materials. This presentation
  will discuss what questions need to be answered to determine if a
  certification program is a good fit for your project. It will also
  discuss the various components of a certification program with a
  focus towards the documentation aspects.</p>

  <list>
    <item><p><link href="http://www.slideshare.net/dlavigne/openhelp11">Slides</link></p></item>
  </list>
</section>

<section id="lana_brindley">
  <title>Open Source Documentation in Four Easy Steps (and one slightly
  more difficult one)</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#lana_brindley"/></p>

  <p>In the world of open source documentation, it is important to
  have a solid process that works. Lana Brindley will discuss how
  things are done at the world’s leading open source company,
  including some of the challenges they face in getting the right
  document into the right hands at the right time, all while keeping
  it open, and keeping it real.</p>

