<section id="david_robbins">
  <title>Remember the User!</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#david_robbins"/></p>

  <p>We live in a world where complexity seems to increase at an
  exponential rate. Regardless of the “space,” information content
  and presentation is more important than ever to efficiently and
  successfully accomplish work. We need to put ourselves in the
  shoes of end-users to understand their tasks in order to create
  information that truly assists their processes. Technical writing
  has contributed much to our understanding of what is needed and
  how to analyze situations to develop information that is both
  useful and usable. But it all comes back to remembering the user.
  As contributors or monitors in collaborative spaces, technical
  writers and help authors have both expertise and a view that is
  needed.</p>
</section>

<section id="shaun_mccance">
  <title>How Mallard saved (and didn’t) GNOME</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#shaun_mccance"/></p>

  <p>GNOME has always faced unique challenges in documentation
  because it has been customized and extended by distributions
  and vendors. This led to the development of Mallard, a dynamic,
  topic-oriented help format designed to support third-party
  additions to documents. Mallard was field tested on some
  application help documents during the GNOME 2 cycle, and in
  GNOME 3 the entire desktop help was rewritten in Mallard. A
  lot of things worked really well. A few things didn’t. Find
  out how GNOME is pushing innovation in user help, and where
  we could still do better.</p>
</section>

<section id="jennifer_zickerman">
  <title>Coordinating Documentation and Support: Turning Complaints
  into Contributions</title>

  <p><link xref="speakers#jennifer_zickerman"/></p>

  <p>One objective — often the most important objective — of software
  documentation is to assist users, which increases user satisfaction
  and reduces support requirements. By implementing open documentation
  platforms, and by coordinating documentation processes with user
  support processes, organizations can engage users who need support
  and convert them into documentation contributors. This presentation
  will describe the efforts that Mozilla’s Thunderbird project is
  undertaking to increase the Thunderbird documentation community by
  recruiting people who are asking (and answering) questions in
  Thunderbird’s support channels.</p>

  <list>
    <item><p><link href="http://www.slideshare.net/jenzed/coordinating-documentation-and-support-turning-complaints-into-contributions">Slides</link></p></item>
